          "body": "The frog plague targets not only Egyptian agriculture and domestic life but Egyptian theology. Heqet, the frog-headed goddess of fertility, was among Egypt's most revered deities, invoked at childbirth and associated with the renewal of life. To fill Egypt with frogs until they invaded ovens, kneading bowls, and beds (8:3) is to transform an object of worship into an instrument of torment. This is not incidental — Exodus's plague narrative is structured as a systematic demolition of the Egyptian pantheon (see Num. 33:4: 'against all the gods of Egypt the LORD executed judgments'). Every plague attacks a sphere of Egyptian divine patronage. The magicians can replicate the frog plague (8:7) — adding to the misery they cannot relieve — demonstrating that their power is real but bounded, derivative, and ultimately counterproductive to Egypt's own interests."
