          "body": "The dialogue between Moses and Pharaoh in 8:25-29 is among the most instructive in Scripture on the anatomy of partial obedience. Pharaoh offers three successive concessions, each designed to achieve Israel's compliance while limiting Yahweh's actual demands. First: 'sacrifice within the land' (8:25) — obey God, but stay under my jurisdiction. Second: 'do not go very far away' (8:28) — go into the wilderness, but keep Egypt in sight. Both offers preserve Pharaoh's supervisory role over Israel's worship. Moses refuses both without apology. The three-days' journey is not Moses's invention; it is what 'the LORD our God commands us' (8:27). The pastoral implication is precise: partial obedience is not obedience. The demand to worship God 'in a way convenient to Egypt' is always the world's offer to the church. Moses's refusal is the model response. Chuck Swindoll notes (*Moses: A Man of Selfless Dedication*) that Moses never once adjusted the divine demand to suit Pharaoh's comfort — not here, not in any plague cycle."
